Some are even convinced that Gozo is the Island of Ogygia and the cave to be the one where the beautiful nymph Calypso kept Odysseus as a "prisoner of love" for seven years.

It is a particularly golden-reddish sand which makes this beach different from all other beaches in Gozo and Malta. Locals refer to this beach as the "Ramla il-Hamra" - the Red Sandy Beach. Roman remains lie beneath the sand and the famous Calypso Cave overlooks the Western side of the beach.

Inside the cave (now collapsed).

Time has not done this attraction any favours. When I first visited (about 15 years ago) you went down the narrow entrance and had a good "window" looking out to sea and felt the magic of the place. Now, the rocks have tumbled and I can't believe it's a safe place to go. It seems like an accident waiting to happen.

This is a place travel agencies or guides do not tell you about. Well, sure, they write about Ramla Bay, it's a beach with reddish sand (far left in the frame). But not about this lookout which is some sort of cave on a hill near by. I found out myself this place existed on a postcard I saw in a tourist shop on Gozo. I just pinpointed a place which I thought would be close on my Tomtom map, drove as far as I could by car and did the rest on foot. When I entered this cave the view blew my mind! I took my gear and all of a sudden this man came climbing UP(!) the cave (from the front that is! I came through the "back door"). It was probably a farmer enjoying the view like I did, but he didn't say anything. I didn't mind, I used him in this shot, which now had a human interest kinda flavour added to it.

The cave itself is boring, dirty and full of papers and trash. Next to the cave is a gift shop and water to drink and free toilets, but they are also dirty. There is a viewing platform but it is very windy.

The Gozo Ministry confirmed that the scan, carried out by the University of Malta, was not conclusive, noting that it had been done "free of charge". 
The cave was closed several years ago as it was considered to be unsafe, following a partial collapse. The popular tourist site was untouched for some time but earlier this year, Wirt Għawdex was commissioned by the government to finance a study on the condition of the cave and the interventions required to preserve it.

The site was popular with tourists, prompting reader Kevin Cutajar to write to the Times of Malta in 2016 lamenting that if the cave were to collapse, it would mean “the Gozitan identity, which we so proudly date back to Calypso, would have lost its place of origin. This is not just an issue of Gozitan pride, but also an issue that impinges on our pockets”.

"Wouldn’t the eventual loss of Calypso’s Cave mean that we have one attraction less to attract tourists to Gozo and to spend their money here? So, what are we waiting for to stop neglecting Calypso’s Cave and to carry out the necessary restoration works?"

Calypso’s Cave in the limits of Xagħra has been analyzed with an advanced technology that produced a 3D image of the site which is renowned for its links with Greek mythology.
The data collection is part of the SIntegraM project under the direction of Professor Saviour Formosa. He said that the project will update Malta’s map in 3D format. Through the technology, using drones and laser scanners, the collected information may be used for the site’s conservation.

Prof. Formosa added that the laser scanners, bought through SIntegraM, collect information from the great depth of the cave which oversees the Ramla l-Ħamra bay. “We have equipment that shoots a thousand point a second and come back with almost two thousand points – this accelerates the gathering of information”.
The 7-million investment SIntergraM is partially financed by European Funds.
